0a855e44-ac5a-4f30-a9ed-31ba14d66563.11f3b15e-d06d-4ac0-a6ea-40cccf69e75f.description=
This operation does not do anything. It can be used to filter flow variables by defining them as inputs and filtering them in the Results tab.

Inputs\:
    field1 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field2 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field3 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.
    field4 – An optional input that can be used for filtering flow variables.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of  "field1" as it was specified at input or when filtered. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

0a855e44-ac5a-4f30-a9ed-31ba14d66563.33a343f0-3893-471a-b73b-bb8b242abbb3.description=This flow updates the ESL CI with RFC number in customer notes and Asset notes. Also updates the Customer contract server size Inputs\: hostName - ESL CI name in short ot FQDN format rfcNumber - RFC number related to the action systemStatus - ESL system status to set (in production, move to obsolescence, deinstalled) 0a855e44-ac5a-4f30-a9ed-31ba14d66563.6dd943ab-1d41-4317-8675-a68b1560f762.description=
Check to see if the value stored in a specified flow variable, denoted by key, is null.

Inputs\:
keyName - The key to check, i.e. the name of the flow variable.

Returns\: 
The value in the specified key, i.e. flow variable.

Responses\:
isNull - If the key is a null pointer, i.e. the flow variable doesn't have an assigned value.
notNull - If some value is stored in the key, i.e the flow variable has a value assigned.
0a855e44-ac5a-4f30-a9ed-31ba14d66563.82133873-cfc2-4ff5-9af1-ec66994452ca.description=This operation writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file, append extra lines to it or even create a new file. Inputs\: source - Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first. contents - The content that should be written to the file. This input field can contain more lines, separated by a delimiter. If it contains the new line character (\n or \r\n), but this is not the delimiter, this character will be escaped and written to file. Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter. delimiter - Specifies the newline delimiter that is used to split the "contents" input field into separate lines that will be further written to the given file. Examples\: \n, \r\n, etc characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. Default\: UTF-8. Valid values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE, ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc. overwrite - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. Default\: true. Valid values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten. Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "success" confirmation message if the operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise. returnCode - It has the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and 1 otherwise. exception - This contains an exception message if the operation fails. Responses\: success - File/directory was written successfully. failure - Unable to write to file/directory, empty contents or source. Examples\: 1. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Windows\: source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt contents\: line1,line2,line3 delimiter\: , 2. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Linux\: source\: /root/example.txt contents\: line1,line2,line3 delimiter\: , 0a855e44-ac5a-4f30-a9ed-31ba14d66563.93b193b0-2dde-497b-a372-1787917088ac.description=
The operation invokes web service methods.  This operation should not be used directly\!  Please use the wizard to build flows that use this operation.

Inputs\:
    xmlTemplate - The template of the soap request to make.
    inputMap - A map used to map between template names and user-friendly names. The template names are pipe-delimited xpaths of the xmltemplate location, with a numerical element for lists.
Value format\: A list of elements separated by the new line delimiter. Eache element hes the format\: \=.
Example\: A line in the "inputMap" could be\: "Request|Details|0|Input|x\=input0.x"
    url - The url to Post to. 
    header_SOAPAction - The SOAPAction http header field, defined by many web services for indicating the intent of the request
    wswAuthenticationType - The authentication type to use for the "username" and "password" input.
Default value\: http
Valid values\: http, ntlm, ws-security digest, ws-security text
    WSSecuritySignRequest - Should the SOAP request be signed using WS-Security.
Default value\: false
Valid values true, false
    WSSecurityEncryptRequest - Should the entire SOAP request be signed using WS-Security.
Default value\: false
Valid values true, false
    WSSecurityTimestampRequest - Should the Timestamp attribute be added to the WS-Security header
Default value\: false
Valid values true, false
    WSSecurityKeystore - Keystore to use for encrypting and signing requests.
    WSSecurityKeystoreType - The type of "WSSecurityKeystore".
    WSSecurityKeystorePassword - The password for "WSSecurityKeystore".
    contentType - Value to be used in the Content-Type HTTP header.
Default value\: text/xml
    characterSet - The character set for HTTP Get request and response.
Default value\: UTF-8
    username - The username to use for authenticating with the web service.
Value format\: For NTLM authentication, the required format is domain\user.
    password - The password to use for authenticating with the web service.
    trustAllRoots - Enables weak security over SSL. A SSH certificate is trusted even if no trusted CA issued it.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    useCookies - Enables cookie tracking. Cookies will be stored between consecutive calls.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    usesJSON - Use JSON arrays for the SOAP Request for all Array types.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false
    timeout - a timeout after which the connection should be terminated or 0 for no timeout.
    socketTimeout - The time to wait for data to be retrieved, in milliseconds. This input needs a value greater than or equal to zero. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
    proxy - A proxy to use when accessing the web service.
    proxyPort - A port on the proxy to connect to.
    proxyUsername - A username to use when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - A password to use when connecting to the proxy.
    keystore - The path to the keystore to use for SSL Client Certificates when using http authentication.
    keystorePassword - The password for the keystore when using http authentication.
    ICONCLUDE_WSW_VERSION - This value is used internally by the operation.
    returnXMLRequest - If this input is set to true, a new output named "rawXMLRequest" is returned from the operation which contains the text of the SOAP request that will be sent. This can be very valuable in troubleshooting.
Default value\: false
Valid values\: true, false

Results\:
    returnCode - This is the primary output. It contains the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and the value -1 otherwise.
    document - Raw XML response.
    documentStripped - Raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with XML XPath operations.
    jsonStripped - Raw XML response stripped of namespaces for ease in parsing with JSON operations, input usesJSON must be set to true for this to be populated.

Responses\:
    success - SOAP request completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes\:
1.If wswAuthenticationType\=ws-security text then this operation transmits passwords in clear-text.
2.Any additional inputs that follow these are added by the Web Service Wizard, and they are specific to the particular web service method being called.
3.If you add new step-level inputs with the name header_, where  is the name of an html header, then that html header will be set to the given value in the HTTP request.
4.This operation will not allow connection through secure transport layers below TLS 1.0.

0a855e44-ac5a-4f30-a9ed-31ba14d66563.c204f985-a0a1-422d-aaa9-8a8d3692a47f.description=Retrieves the server(s) ServerVO properties Inputs\: coreHost - The DNS name or IP Address of your SAS core. corePort - The port to Connect to your SAS core on. coreProtocol - The protocol to connect to your SAS core with. Either HTTP or HTTPS. coreUsername - The username for host. corePassword - The password for host. coreVersion - The version of SAS to use. agent - The agent name search string (can be a partial name and multiple return results can be returned; the matching type for this input can be selected by using the 'matching' flag). matching - A flag that indicates if the search performed using the agent name should be based on a partial or exact match. The default value for this input is 'Begins With'. serverID - The ID of the searched server. This input should be used for unique identification. If provided, then the 'agent' input is ignored. delimiter - The delimiter used to separate the result values. By default the values are comma delimited. Responses\: success - retrieved successfully failure - failed to retrieve data Returns\: createdBy - The name of the user who created this object. createdDate - The date that this object was created. id - The unique ID of this object. dirtyAttributes - A ; delimited list of attributes that are dirty (Modified and not yet fully propagated). modifiedBy - The user who last modified this object. modifiedDate - The date that this object was last modified on. description - The description of this object. hostname - The DNS hostname of this object. model - The model of this object. osVersion - The version of the OS running on the object. primaryIP - The primary IP address of this object. serialNumber - This object's serial number. manufacturer - The manufacturer of this object. name - The name of this object version - The version of this object codeset - The Code set of this object. customerName - The name of the customer this object was created for. defaultGW - The default gateway used when accessing this object. discoveredDate - The date when this object was first discovered. facilityName - The name of the facility housing this object. locale - The locale this object is in. lockComment - The comment on this object's locked. NOTE\: object may not be locked. lockDate - The date this object was last locked. lockUser - The user who locked this object last. isLocked - A boolean value specifying whether or not this object is currently locked. loopbackIP - The loopback ip address used by this object. managementIP - The management ip address used by this object. mid - mid The server's management identifier. NetBIOSName - The full netBIOS (Windows networking) name for this object. lifecycle - The state in the Opsware lifecycle that this object is currently in. origin - The origin of the managed server. ASSIMILATED or PROVISIONED osFlavor - The flavor of the OS running on this object. For example\: Windows. osSPVersion - The service pack version of the OS running on the object. peerIP - The managed server's peer IP address. platformName - The name of the platform. previousSWRegDate -The last time the Opsware agent reported the installed software on the server. realmName - The name of the realm this object is in. realmId - The id of the realm where the server is located. stage - The stage of the managed server. state - The current state of the managed server\: OK, UNREACHABLE or MAINTENANCE use - The intended use of the managed server (i.e. its role in a deployment)\: DEVELOPMENT, STAGING, PRODUCTION or UNKNOWN. virtualizationType - The virtualization type.
